commentThread.commentText: These people are Australians with aboriginal ancestors...that can legally "identify" as Aboriginal. Regardless of being prominently of European decent in alot of cases. Fact of the matter is none of them are Aboriginal without being mixed ethnicity. They can legally identify as aboriginal because their great+ grand parent may or may not have been part native. The last Tasmanian aboriginal died in the 1800s. There are possibly only 30,000 direct descendants left, if that. The discrepancy between this and the 600,000+ listed in the statistics are those that identify as one. Middle Eastern and Europeans dominantly contributed to the mixing of natives over the 1700-1800s. They were almost driven to extinction with only an estimated 60,000 left. Personally I just see Australian's of aboriginal decent. Just as I'm not an indigenous German or indigenous Englishman. I'm Australian with great grandparents that originated from those 2 countries. Definitely changed the way I perceived Indigenous Australians. I realise now that my education has been warped by the view of a coloniser, that has created this intangible criteria of who an Aboriginal person should be. Originally I thought in order to be an Aboriginal you needed to be 'full blood', including skin colour, and still practice traditions from before the Europeans invaded. This standard is almost impossible for a contemporary Aboriginal due to the constant displacement and assimilation that has been carried out through history. It is worrying to see many views, saying they are only 'half-Aboriginal' or 5% etc, which is basically is history of assimilation repeating; where if you were 'white' enough you could blend into white society. No-one, especially non-Indigenous Australians (including me) should determine whether a person should identify as an Aboriginal.

The largest extinction event in Australia's history took place when the first aboriginal people in Australia arrived from southeast Asia 40-60 thousand years ago. They wiped out almost all the native mega-fauna and reduced the rainforest area in Australia by 90%. They also introduced a non native breed of dog, now called the 'Dingo' onto the landmass around 6 thousand years ago which further wiped out more native marsupial species including the Thylacine and Tasmanian Devils from mainland Australia. The reason it seems as though aboriginal people live in harmony with the Australian environment is because by the time Europeans arrived, most of the damage was already done and the ecosystems that make up Australia had mostly reached an equilibrium with the Human inhabitants (who themselves are an invasive species).

I don't know how I led you to believe that but anyway... People care because they are/were the native inhabitants of Australia before British colonisation. People care because what happened to Aboriginal culture was genocide. People care because because it's an issue that deserves to be out in the open and not swept under the rug. People care because without recognising the faults in our history we can never make a better future for the future generations of Australia. It's called compassion and empathy, it's not a hard thing to understand.

In a way I do agree with what you're saying but Aboriginality isn't just the colour of our skin. It is a deep set spiritual connection with the land, it's preserving our stories, customs and traditions that would otherwise be lost if we "don't care too much about what happened in the past". I don't know any Aboriginal person that would hold a personal grudge towards a white person just for what their ancestors did. But I believe it's important we recognise the things that did happen to our people and become a more resilient and accepting country because of these truths. I also believe that no matter what race/culture or backgrounds we come from, we should all be proud of who and what we are as long as we also accept others for the same exact things. I am well aware that no white person today should be held accountable for what their ancestors did, but I think it's important we preserve the past of our great nation, the good and the bad. I am not just Australian, I am an Aboriginal Australian of the Ngembaa tribe, it is a part of my identity as a human being and to be able to say that WE ARE STILL HERE is something I am extremely proud of because of the rough past our country has.

I have no doubts that the Native Americans in the U.S. are oppressed, often overlooked, neglected, and not well represented/catered to/in equal position in mainstream society. However at the same time, the Aboriginals in the second half of the 1900's were getting their children forcibly taken from them and raised in orphanages where they were taught to feel shame for what they were, and were subject to constant physical, psychological, and sexual abuse. Not only in orphanages or foster homes, but also in the aboriginal communities, women and children to this day are at constant risk of victimization for physical and sexual abuse by both aboriginal and white men, both within their family and outside their family. People ignore the issue and those accused can get out of being charged by simply not showing up to court. If people try to get help within the community they are often ignored, ridiculed, or even punished, even by their own family. Children are often forced or coerced into addiction to substances such a s alcohol and petrol sniffing to facilitate the perpetration of sexual abuse. Alcoholism and drugs are also a problem in Native American communities but the circumstances surrounding it are a bit different.

Aboriginal is a term for indigenous people (as in a people native to a certain land), but it also applies to the population of people living specifically in Australia prior to white settlement. Throughout Australian history, Aboriginals have been discriminated against, given fewer rights, and many of those with lighter skin were taken away from their families and forced to become maids and servants to rich white families. Even now, Aboriginals tend to be poorer and much more disadvantaged that many other ethnic groups in Australia due to continuing racism and and a legacy of poverty. However, their culture is extremely rich and colorful, with some of the most beautiful nature artwork of any culture in the world. I think many of the people who will watch this video won't be aware of Australian history, so here's a little background.
